The vertical elevation at the two transects is measured as the average of the ends of the wetted transect line. If one end of the transect line extends off the DEM (which can happen if the DEM raster is tight to the channel), then just the elevation of the the end that exists inside the DEM is used.

Note that the slope is always calculated by subracting the downstream elevation from the upstream elevation. Typically this will produce a positive slope value because the water surface elevation at the bottom of the reach should be below that of the top of the reach. However, negative values can arise in cases where the overall site slope is very low, and there are perturbations in the interpolation of the RBT water surface.',NULL,NULL,2012,'2','2',NULL,'rbt_results/metric_results/site_water_surface_slope','2017-05-23 16:49:59','2017-05-23 23:03:39');

The residual depth at each thalweg location is multiplied by the associated upstream interval. Each of these measurements is summed to produce the final Area Sum value.',NULL,NULL,2012,'2','2',NULL,'rbt_results/metric_results/areasum','2017-05-23 16:49:59','2017-05-23 23:03:39');

The Area Sum value is divided by the site length (to generate the proportional area of the site that is in a pool) and then multiplied by 100 to produce the final RP100 value.',NULL,NULL,2012,'2','2',NULL,'rbt_results/metric_results/rp100','2017-05-23 16:49:59','2017-05-23 23:03:39');

A pool tail crest is located by looping over the list of Thalweg depths and identifying points where the residual depth is greater than zero and the previous depth along the thalweg equals 0 (i.e. not a pool). The depth at each of the identified pool tail crests is summed and then divided by the total number of pools to produce the value of the average pool tail crest depth.',NULL,NULL,2012,'2','2',NULL,'rbt_results/metric_results/pool_tail_crest_depth_avg','2017-05-23 16:49:59','2017-05-23 23:03:39');

A pool is identified as a point or series of points along the Thalweg with a residual depth greater than zero that is bounded by points along the thalweg with a residual depth(s) equaling zero. The maximum depth of each pool is determined by examining all points within a pool and selecting the point with the highest value. The maximum depth value for each pool is summed and then divided by the total number of pools to produce the value for max average depth.',NULL,NULL,2012,'2','2',NULL,'rbt_results/metric_results/pool_max_depth_avg','2017-05-23 16:49:59','2017-05-23 23:03:39');
